{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"503c6339-7266-4e2a-8f0e-60ececd2d468","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To copy the trace off the pod:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look\nIf you just want a live view first:\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), you can [download the standalone](https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace) or use `PerfView` / `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c6fcd9b4-8bf0-4c59-92de-e503a1cd97a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":410,"requestId":"7647:149CB5:D48CA7:F8B832:69FE8CA1"},"id":"079b6107-6f83-405c-9832-8ac14b76d40e","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:23:55.551Z","parentId":"a7d664b8-48a8-4d80-9c57-5d20c8b155ca"}
